# LESSON 2 requests. Server: npm run lesson2  (or lesson2:scaffold)
# In VS Code with the REST Client extension, a Send Request link appears above each.

@host = http://localhost:3200


### 1. GET the animals (already works, even in the scaffold)
# Run this first so the starting three rows are visible.

GET {{host}}/get-all-animals


### 2. POST a new animal
# The endpoint this lesson builds. Before it is written this returns 404,
# which is a useful thing to show first.

POST {{host}}/add-one-animal
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "name": "Falcon",
    "category": "Bird",
    "can_fly": true,
    "lives_in": "Cliffs"
}


### 3. GET again, to prove it saved
# Replying nicely and actually storing the row are two different claims.
# This checks the second one.

GET {{host}}/get-all-animals


### 4. POST with no name
# Nothing stops this yet, so it saves with undefined as the name. A natural
# opening for talking about checking data before saving it.

POST {{host}}/add-one-animal
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "category": "Bird",
    "can_fly": true,
    "lives_in": "Nowhere"
}


### 5. POST with no Content-Type header
# Worth showing on purpose. Nothing parses the body, so req.body is empty.
# It does not crash, it saves undefined, which is worse because it is silent.

POST {{host}}/add-one-animal

{
    "name": "Sparrow",
    "category": "Bird",
    "can_fly": true,
    "lives_in": "Hedges"
}
